00:12:23,210 --> 00:12:27,112
Here in these images I'm using the principle of negative space to imply paths in the woods

259
00:12:27,152 --> 00:12:28,572
that are meant to mislead the player.

260
00:12:29,153 --> 00:12:33,415
Without giving anything away, you can actually get lost by following these paths, so you

261
00:12:33,435 --> 00:12:34,055
can't trust them.

262
00:12:37,156 --> 00:12:38,797
Some more examples of negative space.

263
00:12:39,898 --> 00:12:45,263
On the left, I created a cramped space that is also isolated from the outside, thanks

264
00:12:45,303 --> 00:12:49,486
to this large field of black, this large amount of negative space around the environment.

265
00:12:50,227 --> 00:12:53,910
The player wonders what is lurking around outside of that little window.

266
00:12:55,593 --> 00:12:57,353
And the use of negative space on the right,

267
00:12:57,473 --> 00:12:59,514
it creates anticipation and unease

268
00:12:59,834 --> 00:13:01,614
with the placement of those sewing mannequins.

269
00:13:01,674 --> 00:13:04,735
The player knows that something is going to happen with them

270
00:13:05,195 --> 00:13:07,536
because of how they are positioned relative to the player.

271
00:13:07,696 --> 00:13:09,996
Negative space is a great little technique

272
00:13:10,036 --> 00:13:12,437
to harness that feeling of unease and anticipation.

273
00:13:16,658 --> 00:13:19,819
So arguably the most distinguishing visual elements of faith

274
00:13:20,499 --> 00:13:22,659
and the most popular are these rotoscoped animations

275
00:13:22,699 --> 00:13:23,680
that play throughout the game.

276
00:13:25,074 --> 00:13:29,999
My inspiration was this critics accolade that I saw in the trailer for The Witch in 2015.

277
00:13:30,479 --> 00:13:33,162
It feels like we're watching something we should not be seeing.

278
00:13:33,182 --> 00:13:36,186
There he goes.

279
00:13:39,542 --> 00:13:42,743
And that became my rationale for subjecting the player

280
00:13:42,763 --> 00:13:44,905
to these animated sequences.

281
00:13:45,685 --> 00:13:47,846
I wanted to shatter the expectations of players

282
00:13:47,967 --> 00:13:50,528
who were probably expecting something

283
00:13:50,548 --> 00:13:52,349
like the mini games from Five Nights at Freddy's.

284
00:13:52,969 --> 00:13:55,831
So they were getting used to the chunky pixels

285
00:13:55,931 --> 00:13:58,473
and getting used to how things moved and how things worked.

286
00:13:59,653 --> 00:14:00,894
There's something very unsettling

287
00:14:00,934 --> 00:14:03,355
about suddenly switching visual styles on the viewer,

288
00:14:04,096 --> 00:14:05,797
much like these uncomfortably detailed.

289
00:14:07,099 --> 00:14:09,542
close-up drawings from Spongebob and other cartoons.

290
00:14:10,523 --> 00:14:12,685
When I saw that, I knew that I loved Spongebob.

291
00:14:13,125 --> 00:14:13,766
That was the moment.

292
00:14:14,587 --> 00:14:16,608
It catches the viewer or the player off guard.

293
00:14:17,730 --> 00:14:19,992
So these rotoscoped animations also had the effect

294
00:14:20,032 --> 00:14:21,433
of reaching out to the player.

295
00:14:21,553 --> 00:14:24,036
Again, I wanted this to feel like a cursed game

296
00:14:24,096 --> 00:14:28,700
that was sentient and knew what, knew about the player,

297
00:14:28,740 --> 00:14:31,803
knew their fears, like the game itself wanted to scare them.

298
00:14:32,647 --> 00:14:35,008
