313
00:15:20,005 --> 00:15:21,846
when I, after I edited the original footage,

314
00:15:21,886 --> 00:15:24,787
I edited it to take out frames and mess with the timing

315
00:15:24,827 --> 00:15:26,407
to make it a little more unsettling.

316
00:15:35,772 --> 00:15:37,793
So my process was pretty straightforward.

317
00:15:38,413 --> 00:15:40,294
First, I would wait till my wife was at work.

318
00:15:40,814 --> 00:15:43,155
And then I would scale, then I would get in costume.

319
00:15:43,735 --> 00:15:47,337
Then I would film what I wanted to do.

320
00:15:47,417 --> 00:15:49,758
And it's kind of therapeutic.

321
00:15:50,238 --> 00:15:53,119
So after I was done filming the footage,

322
00:15:53,619 --> 00:15:56,400
I would scale the original footage to my working resolution

323
00:15:56,420 --> 00:15:58,741
and import the frames into Photoshop

324
00:15:59,361 --> 00:16:01,582
and convert it to 15 frames per second.

325
00:16:03,648 --> 00:16:06,171
Then I would hand trace the outline of the character

326
00:16:06,191 --> 00:16:10,156
for the cut scene and fill in things

327
00:16:10,236 --> 00:16:12,499
like the face or any colored fields

328
00:16:12,559 --> 00:16:15,383
that I wanted to have or any solid fields of color

329
00:16:16,264 --> 00:16:17,185
on another video layer.

330
00:16:18,593 --> 00:16:20,835
And then finally, I would add things like facial features

331
00:16:20,875 --> 00:16:23,577
and other elements specifically to the character

332
00:16:23,597 --> 00:16:25,659
on another video layer.

333
00:16:25,839 --> 00:16:28,602
And most of that was, it was a little bit

334
00:16:28,622 --> 00:16:31,144
of key frame animation and then filling in the in-betweens,

335
00:16:31,624 --> 00:16:33,826
but mostly it was just straight ahead animation

336
00:16:34,407 --> 00:16:36,448
where I was just trying to make something grow

337
00:16:36,609 --> 00:16:40,472
out of a face or have blood drip down from a mouth.

338
00:16:41,253 --> 00:16:42,834
It was mostly just straight ahead stuff.

339
00:16:44,502 --> 00:16:46,203
So using Photoshop's video layers,

340
00:16:46,243 --> 00:16:48,063
it was a very non-destructive workflow,

341
00:16:48,143 --> 00:16:49,883
which I really appreciated as an animator.

342
00:16:49,903 --> 00:16:53,284
I probably wouldn't have gotten these done without it.

343
00:16:54,104 --> 00:16:55,505
On average, each rotoscope scene

344
00:16:55,525 --> 00:16:57,445
would involve 75 to 120 drawings.

345
00:17:02,886 --> 00:17:06,487
So the result was a disturbingly lifelike animation

346
00:17:06,707 --> 00:17:08,547
that brought the chunky pixels to life.

347
00:17:10,748 --> 00:17:11,388
This is all me.

348
00:17:11,768 --> 00:17:12,908
There's me in my Texas apron.

349
00:17:14,314 --> 00:17:15,595
It actually required two shots.

350
00:17:17,817 --> 00:17:18,537
There's me in a mirror.

351
00:17:20,999 --> 00:17:22,700
So animating at 15 frames per second

352
00:17:22,740 --> 00:17:24,481
was a smart move, really smart, considering

353
00:17:24,521 --> 00:17:25,682
the amount of drawings I had to do.

354
00:17:26,422 --> 00:17:29,004
Our eyes have kind of our own kind

355
00:17:29,044 --> 00:17:32,547
of natural frame interpolation when we look at moving images

356
00:17:32,627 --> 00:17:33,587
or changing images.

357
00:17:34,068 --> 00:17:37,150
This is something that Richard Williams, a famous animator,

358
00:17:37,190 --> 00:17:38,651
called the persistence of vision.

359
00:17:39,740 --> 00:17:42,281
So we produce an ocular after image

360
00:17:42,301 --> 00:17:45,462
when we look at a changing image,

361
00:17:45,742 --> 00:17:48,402
and basically one frame bleeds into the next frame

362
00:17:48,823 --> 00:17:50,483
and effectively fills in the gaps for us.

363
00:17:51,523 --> 00:17:53,984
A lot of players remark on the smoothness of the animations

364
00:17:54,344 --> 00:17:56,324
when in reality they're running at a very low frame rate.

365
00:17:59,445 --> 00:18:00,725
